mendacious
	v. not telling the truth; lying
promulgated
	v. promote or make widely known (an idea or cause)
serendipitous
	adj. occurring or discovered by change in a happy or beneficial way
commensurate
	adj. corresponding in size or degree; in proportion
heterodox
	adj. not conforming with accepted or orthodox standards or beliefs
perfunctory
	adj. (of an action or gesture) carried out with a minimum of effort or reflection
panacea
	n. a solution or remedy for all difficulties or diseases
sanguine
	adj. optimistic or positive, especially in an apparently bad or difficult situation
irresolute
	adj. showing or feeling hesitancy; uncertain
bucolic
	adj. relating to the pleasant aspects of the countryside and country life